Dallas was historically richer in material wealth than it was hip to the la=
test trends in the culture. If the city had leading art collectors, they we=
ren=E2=80=99t interested in contemporary art. Certainly, you couldn=E2=80=
=99t expect the guys at Caterpillar or ExxonMobil to be enthusiastic about =
seeing the show of an under-represented artist, let alone want to buy their=
 work. That=E2=80=99s changed over the past quarter-century, in part thanks=
 to the efforts of collectors Howard and Cindy Rachofsky, who turned their =
annual TWO x TWO for AIDS and Art fundraiser into a Dallas institution. Mor=
e than a mere charity auction, the party has supported the Dallas Museum of=
 Art=E2=80=99s acquisition of cutting-edge art and helped fuel the growing =
collector community in Dallas, in turn.

Now, that community is at a crossroads. Rachofsky, a fit
octogenarian former hedge fund manager who favors the kind of colorful shir=
ts we used to call =E2=80=9Cloud,=E2=80=9D has decided to step away and let=
 Dallas step up. A little more than a week before I arrived in Dallas, 500 =
people=E2=80=94a mix of local collectors, New York gallerists, some museum =
folks, and art advisors=E2=80=94crammed into a tent next to the Rachofskys=
=E2=80=99 Richard Meier-designed home, where Alan Cumming was emcee and Sot=
heby=E2=80=99s auctioneer Michael Macaulay knocked down more than 100 works=
 of art donated by the artists and their galleries.

The auction raised $10.2 million, including $1.6 million from work by Nicol=
as Party, who was being honored at the auction and shown at Rachofsky=E2=80=
=99s exhibition space, The Warehouse. At the same time, The Warehouse was s=
howing dozens of artworks that had been acquired by the Dallas museum with =
funds raised by TWO x TWO. Over at the museum, an exhibition about represen=
tation in contemporary art, featuring a
wide variety of works, many acquired with TWO x TWO funds, further drove ho=
me the point that the Rachofskys were a wellspring feeding the transformati=
on of what Dallas considers art. One of the hidden benefits of TWO x TWO is=
 that it=E2=80=99s been instrumental in marketing the idea of collecting co=
ntemporary art. That wasn=E2=80=99t so obvious in Dallas a quarter-century =
ago, when taste in art ran toward classic modernism, if there was a taste f=
or art collecting at all.

More than attracting wealthy professionals to the idea of buying contempora=
ry art, TWO x TWO created a relaxed party atmosphere=E2=80=94Chaka Khan per=
formed this year=E2=80=94where art dealers and potential collectors could d=
evelop social relationships that might lead to working relationships. While=
 Dallas has a contemporary art fair in early April, it=E2=80=99s easy to se=
e how much more efficient, cost-effective, and fun it is for a gallery to d=
onate a work by one of its artists to TWO x TWO, in the hope that the
auction will generate interest from underbidders and onlookers. Instead of =
shipping a whole booth of art to Dallas=E2=80=94not a cheap endeavor=E2=80=
=94the gallery owner or director parties in Dallas over a long weekend and =
makes connections that can be followed up on the next time the Dallas colle=
ctor is in New York.

The Rachofskys aren=E2=80=99t giving up on Dallas, they just have some FOMO=
=2E While everyone else was in Paris fo=
r Art Basel, they were hanging art for=
 the auction in their home, which Rachofsky describes as a one-bedroom apar=
tment built atop an art gallery. Next year, they=E2=80=99re hoping to be ha=
ving fun in Paris, too.

They also think it=E2=80=99s time for the rest of the Dallas collecting com=
munity to figure out how to take it from here. As more money flows into Dal=
las from its growing population and the wealth of its broadening industrial=
 and financial base, one of the challenges for an institution like the Dall=
as museum is how to tap into the next generation of
collectors. I=E2=80=99m confident they=E2=80=99ll find a way.

