5e082?utm_campaign=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%2811%2F3%2F24%29&utm_source=
=3Dcustomer.io ) from earlier in the week that makes you wonder what the pa=
per has against Sotheby=E2=80=99s. Focusing on real estate auction sites, i=
ncluding Concierge, which is owned in part by Sotheby=E2=80=99s, the articl=
e took pains to explain how Concierge has a system for giving sellers marke=
t intelligence before committing to a no-reserve sale. Though it cited
one success, the overall tone was negative, more about the sellers=E2=80=99=
 overestimation of the value of their properties than any failure on the pa=
rt of the auctions.

The article ends with a couple who decided to use Concierge to sell their N=
orman Jaffe-designed home on Further Lane in East Hampton. They did so afte=
r Sotheby=E2=80=99s Charlie Stewart, who had rented from the couple during =
the pandemic, recommended the service. The couple believed the 3-acre prope=
rty=E2=80=94once listed for $27.5 million=E2=80=94was worth $20 million for=
 the land alone. The house and land ended up selling for $15 million, plus =
fees. The disappointed seller told the Journal, =E2=80=9CI think I vomited =
and blacked out.=E2=80=9D

Until Tuesday,
