ested in contemporary art. Certainly, you couldn=E2=80=99t expect the guys =
at Caterpillar or ExxonMobil to be enthusiastic about seeing the show of an=
 under-represented artist, let alone want to buy their work. That=E2=80=99s=
 changed over the past quarter-century, in part thanks to the efforts of co=
llectors <b>Howard</b> and <b>Cindy</b> <b>Rachofsky</b>, who turned their =
annual TWO x TWO for AIDS and Art fundraiser into a Dallas institution. Mor=
e than a mere charity auction, the party has supported the Dallas Museum of=
 Art=E2=80=99s acquisition of cutting-edge art and helped fuel the growing =
collector community in Dallas, in turn.<br/><br/>Now, that community is at =
a crossroads. Rachofsky, a fit
octogenarian former hedge fund manager who favors the kind of colorful shir=
ts we used to call =E2=80=9Cloud,=E2=80=9D has decided to step away and let=
 Dallas step up. A little more than a week before I arrived in Dallas, 500 =
people=E2=80=94a mix of local collectors, New York gallerists, some museum =
folks, and art advisors=E2=80=94crammed into a tent next to the Rachofskys=
=E2=80=99 <b>Richard Meier</b>-designed home, where <b>Alan Cumming</b> was=
 emcee and Sotheby=E2=80=99s auctioneer <b>Michael Macaulay</b> knocked dow=
n more than 100 works of art donated by the artists and their galleries.<br=
/><br/>The auction raised $10.2 million, including $1.6 million from work b=
y <b>Nicolas Party</b>, who was being honored at the auction and shown at R=
achofsky=E2=80=99s exhibition space, The Warehouse. At the same time, The W=
arehouse was showing dozens of artworks that had been acquired by the Dalla=
s museum with funds raised by TWO x TWO. Over at the museum, an exhibition =
about representation in contemporary art, featuring a
wide variety of works, many acquired with TWO x TWO funds, further drove ho=
me the point that the Rachofskys were a wellspring feeding the transformati=
on of what Dallas considers art. One of the hidden benefits of TWO x TWO is=
 that it=E2=80=99s been instrumental in marketing the idea of collecting co=
ntemporary art. That wasn=E2=80=99t so obvious in Dallas a quarter-century =
ago, when taste in art ran toward classic modernism, if there was a taste f=
or art collecting at all. <br/><br/>More than attracting wealthy profession=
als to the idea of buying contemporary art, TWO x TWO created a relaxed par=
ty atmosphere=E2=80=94<b>Chaka Khan</b> performed this year=E2=80=94where a=
rt dealers and potential collectors could develop social relationships that=
 might lead to working relationships. While Dallas has a contemporary art f=
air in early April, it=E2=80=99s easy to see how much more efficient, cost-=
effective, and fun it is for a gallery to donate a work by one of its artis=
ts to TWO x TWO, in the hope that the
auction will generate interest from underbidders and onlookers. Instead of =
shipping a whole booth of art to Dallas=E2=80=94not a cheap endeavor=E2=80=
=94the gallery owner or director parties in Dallas over a long weekend and =
makes connections that can be followed up on the next time the Dallas colle=
ctor is in New York. <br/><br/>The Rachofskys aren=E2=80=99t giving up on D=
allas, they just have some FOMO. While everyone else was in Paris for Art B=
asel, they were hanging art for the auction in their home, which Rachofsky =
describes as a one-bedroom apartment built atop an art gallery. Next year, =
they=E2=80=99re hoping to be having fun in Paris, too. <br/><br/>They also =
think it=E2=80=99s time for the rest of the Dallas collecting community to =
figure out how to take it from here. As more money flows into Dallas from i=
ts growing population and the wealth of its broadening industrial and finan=
cial base, one of the challenges for an institution like the Dallas museum =
is how to tap into the next generation of
collectors. I=E2=80=99m confident they=E2=80=99ll find a way. <br/></td>
         </tr>
